= Personal Statement: At Illinois, we value a student’s ability to contribute to a community of inclusion, belonging, and respect where our graduate students can learn and collaborate productively and positively.  \ Please provide an example of how you contributed to or engaged with a community of students or colleagues with different perspectives, abilities, and experiences to achieve a positive outcome, and reflect on what you learned from this experience. (250 words max)

Being surrounded by research communities motivated me to push myself intellectually. When it came time to publish papers, it was this same community that guided me in developing my writing abilities. Early involvement in competitive programming exposed me to diverse algorithmic paradigms and sparked my interest in theoretical computer science. Combined with the mentorship I received in research, this inspired me to create similar opportunities for other students. I founded the Algorithms Club at UTD to introduce students to theory papers and helped them learn about recent algorithmic findings, especially in fair division and online algorithms. Similarly, in the Multimodal Interactions Lab, I mentored students new to the lab, introducing them to HCI literature and the research process. I believe that this experience helped several students from both the club and lab take a deeper interest in research. 

In my PhD, I want to find this same kind of community within theoretical computer science. As I develop my research focus, I hope to be surrounded by people working across approximation algorithms, complexity theory, etc. —scholars who help me see unexpected connections and collaborate on problems at the intersection of these areas. I want to contribute to a community where researchers with different expertise support and challenge each other, just as I am grateful to have experienced during my undergraduate career.
